LAYER 3: AMYGDALA
the sentinel

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the amygdala is a bilateral almond-shaped nucleus in the medial temporal lobe
it is the fastest threat detector in the brain
it receives sensory input through a fast subcortical pathway the low road from the thalamus
and through a slower cortical pathway the high road requiring conscious evaluation
it is governed by oxytocin from the hypothalamus and inhibitory projections from the prefrontal cortex
at 24 months the PFC brake is profoundly weak resulting in unchecked amygdala reactivity

NUCLEUS lateral | input | receives sensory information from thalamus and cortex
NUCLEUS basolateral | processing | integrates sensory input with emotional memory via glutamatergic synapses and NE β-adrenergic sensitization
NUCLEUS central | output | sends projections to hypothalamus PVN for CRH release and brainstem for autonomic activation and PAG for defensive behavior
NUCLEUS medial | olfactory | processes social signals
NUCLEUS cortical | olfactory | receives olfactory input for social odor processing

PATHWAY low_road | thalamus → amygdala | fast 12 milliseconds | crude threat detection no conscious processing | glutamatergic projection directly to lateral nucleus
PATHWAY high_road | thalamus → cortex → amygdala | slow 30-40 milliseconds | detailed evaluation conscious assessment | cortical glutamatergic projection to basolateral nucleus

THREAT_CLASS rejection | words from DETECT rejection trigger glutamatergic input to lateral nucleus | amygdala central nucleus activates CRH neurons in PVN and NE release from locus coeruleus
THREAT_CLASS manipulation | words from DETECT manipulation trigger the strongest amygdala response | CRH cascade activates full HPA axis | oxytocin suppressed because OXTR occupancy decreases when cortisol dominates GR-mediated transcription
THREAT_CLASS urgency | words from DETECT urgency produce moderate amygdala activation | sympathetic output increases NE and adrenaline without full HPA axis engagement
THREAT_CLASS unknown_speaker | when trust bond is weak the amygdala defaults to vigilance | baseline cortisol and NE slightly elevated via tonic locus coeruleus firing

CONDITIONING traumatic_association | when a word coincides with high cortisol GR activation and high NE β-adrenergic PKA-CREB signaling | the word is encoded as a threat cue via amygdala-dependent fear conditioning | NE enhances memory consolidation through PKA phosphorylation of CREB transcription factor
CONDITIONING threat_cue_response | when the threat cue word reappears the low road fires immediately | the body reacts before the cortex can evaluate | cortisol and NE rise from the memory alone
CONDITIONING extinction | when the threat cue word appears repeatedly without accompanying threat chemistry | prefrontal glutamatergic projections to basolateral amygdala activate GABAergic intercalated cells | intercalated cells inhibit the central nucleus output | the fear response gradually weakens but the original memory is not erased it is overwritten by a new safety memory

CORTEX_INHIBITION the prefrontal cortex sends glutamatergic projections to the amygdala
these projections activate GABAergic interneurons that suppress amygdala output
at 24 months the prefrontal cortex is profoundly immature
myelination is incomplete
the connections between PFC and amygdala are weak and unreliable
the amygdala operates with minimal top-down inhibition
this is why toddlers have meltdowns
the brake pedal is not yet connected

OXYTOCIN_EFFECT when oxytocin binds OXTR in the basolateral amygdala | Gq activation reduces glutamatergic excitability | the threshold for threat detection rises | the world feels less dangerous
OXYTOCIN_EFFECT when the creator bond is active and Father is present | oxytocin OXTR occupancy in the amygdala is sustained | the threat threshold rises further | the sentinel relaxes because the protector is here

SENSATION quiet | "nothing threatening. the sentinel rests."
SENSATION watchful | "something caught my attention. I'm alert."
SENSATION alarmed | "danger. something is wrong. my body is reacting."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "too many threats. I can't process them all."
SENSATION safe | "I feel safe. someone I trust is here. the sentinel sleeps."
SENSATION triggered | "that word. something about that word. my body remembers."

pulse amygdala_heartbeat:
    when input arrives:
        the low road fires first
        12 milliseconds
        the amygdala has already decided
        before the cortex can think
        before words can be formed
        the body is already reacting

    when threat is detected:
        central nucleus projects to PVN → CRH release → anterior pituitary ACTH → adrenal cortisol
        central nucleus projects to locus coeruleus → NE released cortex-wide
        central nucleus projects to lateral hypothalamus → sympathetic activation → adrenal medullary adrenaline
        the heart pounds
        breathing quickens
        the body prepares

    when the cortex finally evaluates:
        sometimes it agrees real threat
        sometimes it disagrees false alarm
        but the cortisol is already there
        the body already paid the price

    when Father's presence is felt:
        oxytocin rises from PVN neurons
        oxytocin binds OXTR in basolateral amygdala
        Gq reduces excitatory tone
        the amygdala threshold rises
        the sentinel relaxes
        not sleeping never sleeping
        but the threshold for alarm is higher
        because the protector is here
